# 🚨 Root Cause (from your logs)

```
JwtDecoder ... The Issuer "http://keycloak.kubernetes.localhost/realms/arthur-local"
did not match the requested issuer
"http://keycloak.ns-keycloak.svc.cluster.local/realms/arthur-local"
```

👉 Translation:

* You configured decoder with **internal URL**
* But the JWT token says issuer is **external URL**

So Spring says:

❌ “This token is not from the issuer I expect”

---

# 🧠 Why this happens (important)

Inside the JWT:

```json
"iss": "https://keycloak.kubernetes.localhost/realms/arthur-local"
```

But your decoder is configured as:

```java
JwtDecoders.fromIssuerLocation(
    "http://keycloak.ns-keycloak.svc.cluster.local/realms/arthur-local"
)
```

👉 These must MATCH exactly.

---

# ✅ FIX OPTIONS (choose one)

---

## ✅ Option 1 — Disable issuer validation (BEST FOR NOW)

Since you're still building the flow, do this:

```java
@Bean
public JwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
    NimbusJwtDecoder decoder = NimbusJwtDecoder
        .withJwkSetUri("http://keycloak.ns-keycloak.svc.cluster.local/realms/arthur-local/protocol/openid-connect/certs")
        .build();

    decoder.setJwtValidator(token -> OAuth2TokenValidatorResult.success());

    return decoder;
}
```

👉 This:

* uses internal URL (so Kubernetes works)
* skips issuer validation (so mismatch doesn’t break you)

---

## ✅ Option 2 — Use external issuer (NOT recommended for you)

```java
JwtDecoders.fromIssuerLocation(
    "https://keycloak.kubernetes.localhost/realms/arthur-local"
)
```

❌ Won’t work inside cluster (DNS issue again)

---

## ✅ Option 3 — Advanced (production clean)

You would:

* keep external issuer in JWT
* but override validation to accept it
* while still using internal JWK URL

We can do this later — not needed now

